{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504861"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2380"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2380"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.06,0.61,0.16,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55976"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2380"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41525"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1933"},{"type":"tags","id":"2089"},{"type":"tags","id":"2309"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45718"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55976"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of worsening tinnitus and progressive hearing loss in her left ear. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her external ear canals and tympanic membranes are normal. She reports decreased sensation in the posterior aspect of the left ear canal and over the left side of her face. A 256 Hz tuning fork is placed on her left mastoid process, and the patient reports being able to hear it. Once she can no longer hear the tuning fork abutting her mastoid process, it is placed in line with the ipsilateral external ear canal. The patient reports she can now hear the tuning fork. The same test is repeated on her right ear with similar results. When the tuning fork is placed midline on her forehead, she hears the sound louder in the right ear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Meningioma","Presbycusis","Vestibular schwannoma","M\u00e9ni\u00e8re disease","Vestibular neuritis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with left-sided tinnitus, progressive hearing loss, and facial sensory changes, suggestive of a cerebellopontine angle lesion. The tuning fork tests reveal important diagnostic information:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Positive Rinne test bilaterally (air conduction greater than bone conduction)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Weber test lateralising to the right ear\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese findings indicate left-sided sensorineural hearing loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVestibular schwannoma\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as acoustic neuroma, is the most likely diagnosis. It is a benign tumour of the vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII) in the cerebellopontine angle. Typical symptoms include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Unilateral sensorineural hearing loss (most common)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Tinnitus\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Dizziness or vertigo\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Facial numbness (due to compression of the trigeminal nerve, CN V)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Rarely, facial weakness (due to facial nerve, CN VII, involvement)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Hitzelberger sign (anaesthesia of the posterolateral external ear canal) is present in this case, further supporting the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningioma\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in the cerebellopontine angle and cause similar symptoms. However, it is less common than vestibular schwannoma in this location and typically does not cause the specific pattern of symptoms described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresbycusis\u003C/strong\u003E is age-related hearing loss. It typically presents with bilateral, symmetric, high-frequency sensorineural hearing loss. The unilateral nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms and her relatively young age make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EM\u00e9ni\u00e8re disease\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by episodes of vertigo, fluctuating hearing loss, tinnitus, and aural fullness. While it can cause sensorineural hearing loss, the episodic nature and presence of vertigo are not consistent with this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVestibular neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the vestibular portion of CN VIII, causing acute onset vertigo without hearing loss. The absence of vertigo and the presence of progressive hearing loss make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the clinical presentation and examination findings, vestibular schwannoma is the most likely diagnosis. Further investigation with MRI would be indicated to confirm the diagnosis and determine the size and extent of the tumour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vestibular schwannoma is a well-recognised cause of unilateral sensorineural hearing loss, often accompanied by tinnitus and facial sensory changes.","Rinne and Weber tests are useful bedside examinations to differentiate between conductive and sensorineural hearing loss."],"references":["Koors PD, Thacker LR, Coelho DH. ABR in the diagnosis of vestibular schwannomas: a meta-analysis. Am J Otolaryngol 2013; 34:195. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23332407/","Matthies C, Samii M, Krebs S. Management of vestibular schwannomas (acoustic neuromas): radiological features in 202 cases--their value for diagnosis and their predictive importance. Neurosurgery 1997; 40:469. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9055285/","Bisi MA, Selaimen CM, Chaves KD, Bisi MC, Grossi ML. Vestibular schwannoma (acoustic neuroma) mimicking temporomandibular disorders: a case report. J Appl Oral Sci. 2006 Dec;14(6):476-81. doi: 10.1590/s1678-77572006000600016. PMID: 19089251; PMCID: PMC4327303."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41525"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2380"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41525"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T22:17:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T08:23:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2380"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55976"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"descr